  {
    "id": "1",
    "front": "What is the primary goal of a Design of Experiments (DOE) in computer science contexts?",
    "back": "The primary goal is to systematically plan, conduct, analyze, and interpret controlled tests to evaluate the factors that influence a system's performance or outcome. It aims to efficiently extract maximum information from data while minimizing experimental runs."
  },
  {
    "id": "2",
    "front": "What is the fundamental purpose of Analysis of Variance (ANOVA) in data analysis?",
    "back": "ANOVA is used to compare the means of two or more groups to determine if there is a statistically significant difference between them. It analyzes the variance within groups and between groups to test hypotheses about population means."
  },
  {
    "id": "3",
    "front": "What is the null hypothesis (H₀) for a one-way ANOVA test?",
    "back": "The null hypothesis states that all group population means are equal: H₀: μ₁ = μ₂ = ... = μₖ, where k is the number of groups being compared."
  },
  {
    "id": "4",
    "front": "What does a statistically significant F-statistic in an ANOVA indicate?",
    "back": "A significant F-statistic (typically when its p-value is less than the chosen significance level, α) indicates that there is a statistically significant difference between at least two of the group means, leading to the rejection of the null hypothesis."
  },
  {
    "id": "5",
    "front": "What is the key difference between one-way ANOVA and two-way ANOVA?",
    "back": "One-way ANOVA analyzes the effect of a single independent variable (factor) on a dependent variable. Two-way ANOVA analyzes the effect of two independent variables on a dependent variable, and can also test for an interaction effect between the two factors."
  }
\]
